    "body": "### Problem\n\nFirst of all, thanks to all who are involved with this project ðŸ™‡ \n\nI frequently use `:%s` to substitute across the current file. I recently updated my work computer to 0.11.0 and lost a behavior that I rate highly. \n\nI previously could hit any key while confirming substitution and get a visual selection indication of what is going to be substituted next. Iâ€™ve taken a screenshot on my personal computer (which still runs 0.10.0) to make this more obvious.\n\nConsider inputting `:%s/RUN/funnnnnn/gc` and hitting enter. That gets me to the first screenshot.\n\nIt appears that hitting any letter other than `n/y/q/a/ ect.` (in this case) highlights all occurrences of the search pattern and shows what will be updated. This was very helpful as it made it easier to go through the substitution with `nyyny` and so on.\n\nThe alternative I've adopted is using `hlsearch`, but this needs to be turned off when I'm done substituting. Any thoughts? \n\n<img width=\"838\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/281727c6-b22f-425c-82be-7f4380401741\" />\n\n<img width=\"840\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/742f826a-b346-4098-8795-21f5cfa4db24\" />\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\nusing nvim 0.10.x\n```bash\necho 111 > temp.txt\necho 222 > temp.txt\necho 111 > temp.txt\necho 111 > temp.txt\necho 111 > temp.txt\necho 111 > temp.txt\nnvim temp.txt\n:%s/111/333/gc\nv # hit any key to show that all occurrences of `111` are highlighted.\n```\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nHitting any key while in the process of `%s` will highlight all occurrences of `111`\n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.x\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nUnsure.\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS 15.5\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nwezterm 20240203-110809-5046fc22\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nhomebrew",
